# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: boiler
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] An **absorption-compression heat pump** (**ACHP**) is a device that integrate an electric compressor in an absorption heat pump.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] In some cases this is obtained by combining a vapor-compression heat pump and an absorption heat pump.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] It is also referred to as a hybrid heat pump which is however a broader field.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Thanks to this integration, the device can obtain cooling and heating effects using both thermal and electrical energy sources.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This type of systems is well coupled with cogeneration systems where both heat and electricity are produced.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Depending on the configuration, the system can maximize heating and cooling production from a given amount of fuel, or can improve the temperature (hence the quality) of waste heat from other processes.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This second use is the most studied one and has been applied to several industrial applications.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The first absorption-compression heat pump cycle concept was patented by Osenbrück.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Little research on it was done in the following years.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] in the 70s, the energy saving potential of the cycle grew in interest and there was a rapid increase in research activities in the field.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] In this period several experimental plants were built and in 1997, Groll summarized this activities in its review where he identified more than 40 studies.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] At that time, considerable work was still needed before the ACHP could become commercially available.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Nordtvedt studied the cycle in his doctoral thesis and his studies ended up in the construction, in 2011, of the first commercial application in the Norwegian Food Industry.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] After this, several units have been installed for commercial use in various high temperature industrial applications.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The main advantage with respect to compression heat pump is that the compression-absorption heat pumps allow the heat to be transfer with a temperature glide.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The compression heat pump uses a single pure working fluid, hence exchanges heat at a constant temperature.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The absorption-compression heat pump uses instead a binary mixture where the condensation and evaporation occur with a temperature glide.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This property increases the efficiency of the heat transfer when the heat source also has a significant temperature glide, which is the typical condition found when dealing with waste heat recovery.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Being a hybrid solution that can exploit both heat and mechanical/electric energy sources, the device can be perfectly coupled with cogeneration units to produce heating and cooling at very high efficiencies.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Moreover, it makes the system more flexible, allowing the optimization of the mix of electricity and thermal energy.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Their availability vary in fact along the day and the year.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Therefore the flexibility allow to reduce the operating costs.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The main drawback of this technology is that, to achieve good performances, they typically need to employ ammonia, which is very toxic and flammable.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This drawback resulted in the fact that these applications remained limited to the industrial sector, where it is more practical dealing with dangerous fluids.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The most studied configuration is the so-called *compression heat pump with solution cycle* (CHPS) or *compression resorption heat pump* (CRHP), where the compressor is in parallel to the electric pump located between the absorber and the desorber.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This configuration is used to increase the temperature of waste heat since it allow high absorption temperature at lower pressure than compression heat pumps.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Another possible configuration for the absorption compression heat pump is obtained from the combination of a gas-driven absorption heat pump (GAHP) with a vapor-compression heat pump.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This configuration arises from the consideration that both cycles have in common a condenser, a lamination valve, and an evaporator.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The main difference between the two is in the compression phase: where the compression heat pump uses an electric compressor, the gas-driven absorption heat pump uses a thermal compressor.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The ACHP is obtained by combining the components that are in common and using the electric and thermal compressor in parallel or in series.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Compression heat pumps use only a single fluid which is a refrigerant.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] In contrast, absorption heat pump requires two fluids, a refrigerant and an absorbent able to absorb it.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] By combining the two devices, proper refrigerant absorbent pairs compatible with both the cycles are needed.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] There is a wide choice of refrigerants available for compression heat pumps.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The absorption cycle is the one limiting the choice of the refrigerant.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The most common refrigerants for absorption systems are ammonia and water.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Both are good for combined absorption-compression heat pumps.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Ammonia has an exceptionally good solubility in water.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This is an important aspect that increases the performance and decreases the size of the device.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] However, its high toxicity and flammability reduces its attractiveness.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Water is a very attractive refrigerant because it is abundant, non-toxic, non-flammable and highly soluble in lithium bromide (LiBr).
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The main issue with water is that, at the typical heat pump evaporator pressures, it freezes at 0 °C.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This makes water unsuitable for the applications where the cold sink goes below 0 °C, which is the typical winter operating condition of an air source heat pump.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The absorbent and refrigerant are strictly related to each other.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] In the case that ammonia is used as refrigerant, the most common absorbent is water.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] In the case that water is used as refrigerant, as previously mentioned, the absorbent is usually LiBr.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Ionic liquids have also been proposed as good absorbents, specially for water as refrigerant.
[src:boiler/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The main advantages of these salts is that they can be used under the conditions at which LiBr solution runs the risk of crystallization and they are less corrosive.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] An **absorption refrigerator** is a refrigerator that uses a heat source to provide the energy needed to drive the cooling process.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] Solar energy, burning a fossil fuel, waste heat from factories, and district heating systems are examples of heat sources that can be used.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] An absorption refrigerator uses two coolants, the first coolant performing evaporative cooling before being absorbed into the second coolant.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] Heat is then needed to reset the two coolants to their initial states.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigerators are commonly used in recreational vehicles (RVs), campers, and caravans because the heat required to power them can be provided by either a propane fuel burner, a low-voltage DC electric heater (from a battery or vehicle electrical system) or a mains-powered electric heater.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigerators can also be used to air-condition buildings using the waste heat from a gas turbine or water heater in the building.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] Using waste heat from a gas turbine makes the turbine very efficient because it first produces electricity, then hot water, and finally, air-conditioning—trigeneration.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] Unlike more common vapor-compression refrigeration systems, an absorption refrigerator has no moving parts.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigerators are an alternative to compressor refrigerators where electricity is unreliable, costly, or unavailable; where noise from the compressor is problematic; or where surplus heat is available.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] In 1748 in Glasgow, William Cullen invented the basis for modern refrigeration, although he is not credited with a usable application.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] More on history of refrigeration can be found in the paragraph Refrigeration Research on page Refrigeration.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigeration uses the same principle as adsorption refrigeration, which was invented by Michael Faraday in 1821.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] Instead of using a solid adsorber, an absorber in an absorption system absorbs the refrigerant vapour into a liquid.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption cooling was invented by the French scientist Ferdinand Carré in 1858.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] The original design used water and sulphuric acid.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] The principle was enhanced with a three-fluid configuration in 1922 by Baltzar von Platen and Carl Munters, two students at the Royal Institute of Technology in Stockholm.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] This "Platen-Munters" design can operate without a pump.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] Commercial production began in 1923 by the newly-formed company *AB Arctic*, which was bought by Electrolux in 1925.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] In the 1960s, absorption refrigeration saw a renaissance due to the substantial demand for refrigerators for caravans.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] AB Electrolux later established a subsidiary in the United States, named Dometic Sales Corporation.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] The company marketed refrigerators for recreational vehicles (RVs) under the *Dometic* brand.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] In 2001, Electrolux sold most of its leisure products line to the venture-capital company EQT which created *Dometic* as a stand-alone company.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] Dometic still sold absorption fridges as of July 2025.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] In 1926, Albert Einstein and his former student Leó Szilárd proposed an alternative design known as the Einstein refrigerator.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] At the 2007 TED Conference, Adam Grosser presented his research of an "intermittent absorption" vaccine refrigeration unit for use in third world countries.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] The refrigerator is a small unit placed over a campfire, that can later be used to cool 15 litres (3.3 imp gal; 4.0 US gal) of water to just above freezing for 24 hours in a 30 °C (86 °F) environment.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] The concept was similar to an early refrigeration device known as an Icyball.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] Common absorption refrigerators use a refrigerant with a very low boiling point (less than −18 °C (0 °F)) just like compressor refrigerators.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] Compression refrigerators typically use an HCFC or HFC, while absorption refrigerators typically use ammonia or water and need at least a second fluid able to absorb the coolant, the *absorbent*, respectively water (for ammonia) or brine (for water).
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] Both types use evaporative cooling: when the refrigerant evaporates (boils), it takes some heat away with it, providing the cooling effect.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] The main difference between the two systems is the way the refrigerant is changed from a gas back into a liquid so that the cycle can repeat.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] An absorption refrigerator changes the gas back into a liquid using a method that needs only heat, and has no moving parts other than the fluids.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] The system thus silently provides for the mechanical circulation of the liquid without a usual pump.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] A third fluid, gaseous, is usually added to avoid pressure concerns when condensation occurs (see below).
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] In comparison, a compressor based heat pump works by pumping refrigerant gas from an evaporator to a condenser.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] This reduces the pressure and boiling temperature in the evaporator and increases the pressure and condensing temperature in the condenser.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] Energy from an electric motor or internal combustion engine is required to operate the compressor pump.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] Compressing the refrigerant uses this energy to do work on the gas, increasing its temperature.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] The warm, high pressure gas then enters the condenser where it undergoes a phase change to a liquid and releases heat to the condenser's surroundings.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] Warm liquid refrigerant moves from the high pressure condenser to the low pressure evaporator via an expansion valve, also known as a throttling valve or a Joule-Thomson valve.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] The expansion valve partially vaporizes the refrigerant cooling it via evaporative cooling, and the resulting vapor is cooled via expansive cooling.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] This is a combination of Joule-Thomson cooling and work done by the expanding gas, both at the expense of the internal energy of the gas.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] The cold, low pressure liquid refrigerant will now absorb heat from the evaporator's surroundings and vaporize.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] The resulting gas enters the compressor, and the cycle begins again.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] A simple absorption refrigeration system common in large commercial plants uses a solution of lithium bromide or lithium chloride salt and water.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] Water under low pressure is evaporated from the coils that are to be chilled.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] The water is absorbed by a lithium bromide/water solution.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] The system drives the water out of the lithium bromide solution with heat.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] Another variant uses air, water, and a salt water solution.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] The intake of warm, moist air is passed through a sprayed solution of salt water.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] The spray lowers the humidity but does not significantly change the temperature.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] The less humid, warm air is then passed through an evaporative cooler, consisting of a spray of fresh water, which cools and re-humidifies the air.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] Humidity is removed from the cooled air with another spray of salt solution, providing the outlet of cool, dry air.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] The salt solution is regenerated by heating it under low pressure, causing water to evaporate.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] The water evaporated from the salt solution is re-condensed, and rerouted back to the evaporative cooler.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] A single-pressure absorption refrigerator takes advantage of the fact that a liquid's evaporation rate depends upon the *partial* pressure of the vapor above the liquid and goes up with lower partial pressure.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] The refrigerator uses three substances: ammonia, hydrogen gas, and water.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] The cycle is closed, with all hydrogen, water and ammonia collected and endlessly reused.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] The cooling cycle starts with liquid ammonia at room temperature entering the evaporator.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] The volume of the evaporator is greater than the volume of the liquid, with the excess space occupied by a mixture of gaseous ammonia and hydrogen.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] The presence of hydrogen lowers the partial pressure of the ammonia gas, thus lowering the evaporation point of the liquid below the temperature of the refrigerator's interior.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] Ammonia evaporates, taking a small amount of heat from the liquid and lowering the liquid's temperature.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] It continues to evaporate, while the large enthalpy of vaporization (heat) flows from the warmer refrigerator interior to the cooler liquid ammonia and then to more ammonia gas.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] In the next two steps, the ammonia gas is separated from the hydrogen so it can be reused.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] The next step separates the ammonia and water.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] The ammonia/water solution flows to the generator (boiler), where heat is applied to boil off the ammonia, leaving most of the water (which has a higher boiling point) behind.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] Some water vapor and bubbles remain mixed with the ammonia; this water is removed in the final separation step, by passing it through the separator, an uphill series of twisted pipes with minor obstacles to pop the bubbles, allowing the water vapor to condense and drain back to the generator.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] The pure ammonia gas then enters the condenser.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] In this heat exchanger, the hot ammonia gas transfers its heat to the outside air, which is below the boiling point of the full-pressure ammonia, and therefore condenses.
[src:boiler/absorption-refrigerator] The condensed (liquid) ammonia flows down to be mixed with the hydrogen gas released from the absorption step, repeating the cycle.
[src:boiler/air-mixing-plenum] An **air-mixing plenum** (or mixing box) is used in building services engineering and HVAC construction for mixing air from different ductwork systems.
[src:boiler/air-mixing-plenum] Air streams are mixed to save energy and improve energy efficiency by partially recirculating conditioned air.
[src:boiler/air-mixing-plenum] The most common application for an air-mixing plenum is the mixing of *return air* (or *extract air*) with fresh air to provide a supply air mixture for onward distribution to the building or area which the ventilation system is serving.
[src:boiler/air-mixing-plenum] The air transferred from the return air stream to the supply air stream is termed *recirculated air*.
[src:boiler/air-mixing-plenum] All air not mixed is rejected to the atmosphere as *exhaust air*.
[src:boiler/air-mixing-plenum] The mixing plenum normally combines two air streams, and includes for three sets of dampers: one for the fresh air, one for the exhaust air, and a mixing damper between the two air streams.
[src:boiler/air-mixing-plenum] The mix of fresh air and recirculated air can thus be adjusted to suit the needs of the building's occupants.
[src:boiler/air-mixing-plenum] Most systems will use motorized dampers to control the air mixing, and controlled by the building management system (BMS), or controls system.
[src:boiler/air-mixing-plenum] Typically as the fresh air and exhaust air dampers are driven from 0% open to 100% open, the mixing damper will in turn be driven from 100% open to 0% open, so as to always ensure a constant volume of supply and extract air.
[src:boiler/air-mixing-plenum] Air supply to a building is generally performed by an air handling unit.
[src:boiler/air-mixing-plenum] The process may include filtering, heating, cooling, humidification, or dehumidification, all of which consume energy.
[src:boiler/air-mixing-plenum] Since building occupants demand less than 100% fresh air, only a fraction of that amount is admitted to the system, with and equal amount of treated air exhausted to the atmosphere; fresh air is mixed with conditioned air in a plenum.
[src:boiler/air-mixing-plenum] Enhanced controls systems may monitor the return air quality or carbon dioxide concentration in order to automatically modulate the air mix for optimum energy efficiency while maintaining desired fresh air requirements.
[src:boiler/air-mixing-plenum] Such systems work very well in buildings where the occupancy rate can vary greatly throughout the day, or seasonally.
[src:boiler/air-mixing-plenum] Additionally, when outside air conditions are such, typically mid-season weather conditions, it may be that ambient temperatures are suitable for free cooling purposes.
[src:boiler/air-mixing-plenum] In such conditions the mixing damper will be set to close and the system use full fresh air for optimum energy efficiency.
[src:boiler/air-mixing-plenum] Where fresh air is not required, such as early morning pre-heat or pre-conditioning periods, the mixing damper can be automatically set to full recirculation, again for optimum energy efficiency.
[src:boiler/ashrae-handbook] The **ASHRAE Handbook** is the four-volume flagship publication of the nonprofit technical organization **ASHRAE** (**American Society of Heating, Refrigerating and Air-Conditioning Engineers**).
[src:boiler/ashrae-handbook] This Handbook is considered the most comprehensive and authoritative repository of practical knowledge on the various topics that form the field of heating, ventilation, air-conditioning, and refrigeration (HVAC&R).
[src:boiler/ashrae-handbook] The four volumes are *Fundamentals*, *Refrigeration*, *HVAC Applications* ("Applications"), and *HVAC Systems and Equipment* ("Systems and Equipment").
[src:boiler/ashrae-handbook] Members of ASHRAE receive the current volume, in both print and CD-ROM form, each year as a basic membership benefit.
[src:boiler/ashrae-handbook] An enhanced electronic version, known as *ASHRAE Handbook Online* is a web-based version updated annually that contains the four latest volumes as well as extra content such as calculations, demonstration videos, and spreadsheets.
[src:boiler/ashrae-handbook] The various versions of the Handbook are typically available to the public via technical, and other, libraries and bookstores.
[src:boiler/ashrae-handbook] The ASHRAE Handbook has had a variety of titles.
[src:boiler/ashrae-handbook] It began in 1922 as the **ASH&VE Guide**.
[src:boiler/ashrae-handbook] In 1973 it became the ASHRAE Handbook, and in 1985 separate publication of inch-pound (I-P) and international system (SI) units versions of the volumes began.
[src:boiler/ashrae-handbook] Stephen Comstock, and the Editor is Mark S.
[src:boiler/ashrae-handbook] The Handbook is published by ASHRAE from its headquarters in Atlanta, Georgia.
[src:boiler/ashrae-handbook] The Handbook's content is created and modified by volunteers via ASHRAE's many Technical Committees (TCs), and then edited and formatted by professional staff at ASHRAE.
[src:boiler/ashrae-handbook] For example, three chapters, in three different volumes, are maintained by TC 5.3, Room Air Distribution.
[src:boiler/ashrae-handbook] Each chapter within a particular volume is reviewed and revised in a repeating four-year cycle; one volume is printed each year.
[src:boiler/ashrae-handbook] In the summer of 2017 the new Fundamentals' volume was released.
[src:boiler/ashrae-handbook] ASHRAE's Handbook Committee maintains an *Authors and Revisers Guide,* which can be obtained freely via the Handbook portion of the ASHRAE Web site.
[src:boiler/ashrae-handbook] While each new or revised chapter manuscript is to be reviewed for technical content by each TC voting and corresponding member before publication, there are often many other pre- and post-publication reviewers.
[src:boiler/ashrae-handbook] For example, members of the Society's Handbook Committee and the College of Fellows review chapters each year.
[src:boiler/ashrae-handbook] Reviews, from basic comments to detailed new content, are encouraged from all users of the Handbook and may be submitted through an online commenting system.
[src:boiler/ashrae] The **American Society of Heating, Refrigerating and Air-Conditioning Engineers** (**ASHRAE** /ˈæʃreɪ/ *ASH-ray*) is an American professional association seeking to advance heating, ventilation, air conditioning and refrigeration (HVAC&R) systems design and construction.
[src:boiler/ashrae] ASHRAE has over 50,000 members in more than 130 countries worldwide.
[src:boiler/ashrae] ASHRAE's members comprise building services engineers, architects, mechanical contractors, building owners, equipment manufacturers' employees, and others concerned with the design and construction of HVAC&R systems in buildings.
[src:boiler/ashrae] The society funds research projects, offers continuing education programs, and develops and publishes technical standards to improve building services engineering, energy efficiency, indoor air quality, and sustainable development.
[src:boiler/ashrae] ASHRAE was founded in 1894 at a meeting of engineers in New York City, formerly headquartered at 345 East 47th Street (the United Engineering Center), and has held an annual meeting since 1895.
[src:boiler/ashrae] Until 1954 it was known as the American Society of Heating and Ventilating Engineers (ASHVE); in that year it changed its name to the American Society of Heating and Air-Conditioning Engineers (ASHAE).
[src:boiler/ashrae] Its current name and organization came from the 1959 merger of ASHAE and the American Society of Refrigerating Engineers (ASRE).
[src:boiler/ashrae] Despite having 'American' in its name, ASHRAE is a global organization, holding international events.
[src:boiler/ashrae] In 2012, it rebranded itself with a new logo and tagline: "Shaping Tomorrow's Built Environment Today".
[src:boiler/ashrae] The ASHRAE Handbook is a four-volume resource for HVAC&R technology and is available in both print and electronic versions.
[src:boiler/ashrae] The volumes are *Fundamentals*, *HVAC Applications*, *HVAC Systems and Equipment*, and *Refrigeration*.
[src:boiler/ashrae] One of the four volumes is updated each year.
[src:boiler/ashrae] ASHRAE also publishes a set of standards and guidelines relating to HVAC systems and issues, that are often referenced in building codes and used by consulting engineers, mechanical contractors, architects, and government agencies.
[src:boiler/ashrae] These standards are periodically reviewed, revised and republished.
[src:boiler/ashrae] The society also publishes two magazines: the *ASHRAE Journal* is issued monthly, and *High Performing Buildings Magazine* is published quarterly.
[src:boiler/ashrae] They contain articles on related technology, information on upcoming meetings, editorials, and case studies of various well-performing buildings.
[src:boiler/ashrae] ASHRAE also publishes books, *ASHRAE Transactions*, and the *International Journal of HVAC&R Research*.
[src:boiler/ashrae] ASHRAE supported the Streamlining Energy Efficiency for Schools Act of 2014 (H.R.
[src:boiler/ashrae] 4092; 113th Congress), a bill that would require the United States Department of Energy to establish a centralized clearinghouse to disseminate information on federal programs, incentives, and mechanisms for financing energy-efficient retrofits and upgrades at schools.
[src:boiler/ashrae] ASHRAE offers six categories of awards: achievement awards to recognize personal honors; personal awards for general and specific society activities; paper awards; society awards for groups or chapters; chapters and regional awards.
[src:boiler/ashrae] ASHRAE Fellow is a Membership Grade of Distinction conferred by The College of Fellows of ASHRAE, Inc. to an ASHRAE member with significant publications or innovations and distinguished scientific and engineering background in the fields of heating, refrigeration, air conditioning, ventilation.
[src:boiler/ashrae] The ASHRAE Fellow membership grade is the highest elected grade in ASHRAE.
[src:boiler/ashrae] ASHRAE has a Hall of Fame honoring "deceased members who have made milestone contributions to the growth of ASHRAE-related technology.
[src:boiler/ashrae] To demonstrate the Society's commitment to sustainability, ASHRAE renovated its previous headquarters building in Atlanta, Ga.
[src:boiler/ashrae] After the renovation and occupancy in June 2008, the building received many awards, including an Energy Star rating with a score of 95, a Platinum Certification from USGBC's LEED program, and four Green Globes from the Green Building Initiative.
[src:boiler/ashrae] The current site energy use intensity (EUI) is 35.8 kBtu/Sqft (411 MJ/m2), a 60 percent reduction from the pre-renovation value.
[src:boiler/ashrae] The renovation included the use of a dedicated outdoor air supply (DOAS) system with energy recovery and humidity control; a ground-source heat pump system; and variable refrigerant flow systems with heat recovery.
[src:boiler/ashrae] The building also serves as a live case study.
[src:boiler/ashrae] A web-based user interface allowed researchers around the world to extract data from the building to study factors such as energy use and electric power demand, water consumption and indoor air quality.
[src:boiler/ashrae] In 2018, ASHRAE decided to move their world headquarters, settling on retrofitting a 1970s-era building in Peachtree Corners, suburban Atlanta.
[src:boiler/ashrae] Completed in 2022, the building has been renovated to comply with ASHRAE's own standards, including ASHRAE 90.1, and the organization has the goal of operating the building at net-zero energy, powered by a large on-site solar array.
[src:boiler/asme] Founded as an engineering society focused on mechanical engineering in North America, ASME is today multidisciplinary and global.
[src:boiler/asme] ASME has over 85,000 members in more than 135 countries worldwide.
[src:boiler/asme] ASME was founded in 1880 in response to numerous steam boiler pressure vessel failures by Alexander Lyman Holley, Henry Rossiter Worthington, John Edison Sweet and Matthias N.
[src:boiler/asme] Forney, with Robert Henry Thurston as the society's founding president.
[src:boiler/asme] Known for setting codes and standards for mechanical devices, ASME conducts one of the world's largest technical publishing operations.
[src:boiler/asme] It holds numerous technical conferences and hundreds of professional development courses each year and sponsors numerous outreach and educational programs.
[src:boiler/asme] Ned Djilali and Georgia Tech president and woman engineer supporter Blake R Van Leer were executive members.
[src:boiler/asme] Kate Gleason and Lydia Weld were the first two women members.
[src:boiler/asme] ASME is one of the oldest standards-developing organizations in America.
[src:boiler/asme] It produces approximately 600 codes and standards covering many technical areas, such as fasteners, plumbing fixtures, elevators, pipelines, and power plant systems and components.
[src:boiler/asme] ASME's standards are developed by committees of subject matter experts using an open, consensus-based process.
[src:boiler/asme] Many ASME standards are cited by government agencies as tools to meet their regulatory objectives.
[src:boiler/asme] ASME standards are therefore voluntary, unless the standards have been incorporated into a legally binding business contract or incorporated into regulations enforced by an authority having jurisdiction, such as a federal, state, or local government agency.
[src:boiler/asme] ASME's standards are used in more than 100 countries and have been translated into numerous languages.
[src:boiler/asme] The largest ASME standard, both in size and in the number of volunteers involved in its preparation, is the ASME Boiler and Pressure Vessel Code (BPVC).
[src:boiler/asme] The BPVC provides rules for the design, fabrication, installation, inspection, care, and use of boilers, pressure vessels, and nuclear components.
[src:boiler/asme] The code also includes standards on materials, welding and brazing procedures and qualifications, nondestructive examination, and nuclear in-service inspection.
[src:boiler/asme] In addition to academic journals, since 1880 the ASME has also published the magazine *Mechanical Engineering*.
[src:boiler/asme] This means the nominees need not be professional educators.
[src:boiler/asme] (1879–1964), an ASME Member and professor of mechanical engineering and head of the department at the Polytechnic Institute of Brooklyn, established the Medal.
[src:boiler/asme] ASME runs several annual E-Fests, or Engineering Festivals, taking the place of the Student Professional Development Conference (SPDC) series.
[src:boiler/asme] In addition to the Human Powered Vehicle Challenge (HPVC), the Innovative Additive Manufacturing 3D Challenge (IAM3D), the Student Design Competition, and the Old Guard Competition, there are also talks, interactive workshops, and entertainment.
[src:boiler/asme] These events allows students to network with working engineers, host contests, and promote ASME's benefits to students as well as professionals.
[src:boiler/asme] E-Fests are held in four regions in the United States and internationally—western U.S, eastern U.S., Asia Pacific, and South America—with the E-Fest location for each region changing every year.
[src:boiler/asme] ASME holds a variety of competitions every year for engineering students from around the world.
[src:boiler/asme] ASME has four key offices in the United States, including its headquarters operation in New York, N.Y., and three international offices in Beijing, China; Brussels, Belgium, and New Delhi, India.
[src:boiler/asme] ASME has two institutes and 32 technical divisions within its organizational structure.
[src:boiler/asme] In 1982, ASME was found to be the first non-profit organization to in violation of the Sherman Antitrust Act.
[src:boiler/asme] The United States Supreme Court found the organization liable for more than $6 million in *American Society of Mechanical Engineers v.
[src:boiler/astm-international] In 1898, a group of scientists and engineers, led by chemist, industry leader, and proponent of standardization Charles Dudley, formed the American Society for Testing Material (ASTM) to address the frequent rail breaks affecting the fast-growing railroad industry.
[src:boiler/astm-international] The group developed a standard for the steel used to fabricate rails.
[src:boiler/astm-international] In 1961 the name "American Society for Testing and Materials" was adopted.
[src:boiler/astm-international] In 2001, ASTM officially changed its name to "ASTM International" and added the tagline "Standards Worldwide".
[src:boiler/astm-international] In 2014, the tagline changed to "Helping our World Work better." ASTM International had offices in Belgium, Canada, China, Peru, Washington, D.C., and West Conshohocken, PA.
[src:boiler/astm-international] In April 2016, the Safety Equipment Institute (SEI) became a subsidiary of ASTM International.
[src:boiler/astm-international] SEI is an accredited third-party certification organization that certifies various types of personal protective equipment to industry consensus standards.
[src:boiler/astm-international] On June 9, 2022, it was announced that the European Committee for Standardization (CEN) and ASTM International agreed to extend and expand a Technical Cooperation Agreement from 2019.
[src:boiler/astm-international] Membership in the organization is open to anyone interested in its activities.
[src:boiler/astm-international] Standards are developed within committees, and new committees are formed as needed, upon request of interested members.
[src:boiler/astm-international] Membership in most committees is voluntary and is initiated by the member's request, not by appointment or invitation.
[src:boiler/astm-international] Members are classified as users, producers, consumers, and "general interest".
[src:boiler/astm-international] The latter includes academics and consultants.
[src:boiler/astm-international] Users include industry users, who may be producers in the context of other technical commodities, and end-users such as consumers.
[src:boiler/astm-international] To meet the requirements of antitrust laws, producers must constitute less than 50% of every committee or subcommittee, and votes are limited to one per producer company.
[src:boiler/astm-international] Because of these restrictions, there can be a substantial waiting-list of producers seeking organizational memberships on the more popular committees.
[src:boiler/astm-international] Members can participate without a formal vote and their input will be fully considered.
[src:boiler/astm-international] As of 2015, ASTM has more than 30,000 members, including over 1,150 organizational members, from more than 140 countries.
[src:boiler/astm-international] The members serve on one or more of 140+ ASTM Technical Committees.
[src:boiler/astm-international] ASTM International has several awards for contributions to standards authorship, including the ASTM International Award of Merit (the organization's highest award) ASTM International is classified by the United States Internal Revenue Service as a 501(c)(3) nonprofit organization.
[src:boiler/astm-international] In 2018, ASTM International launched the Additive Manufacturing Center of Excellence (AM CoE), a global initiative uniting industry, government, and academia to accelerate research, development, standardization, certification, and industrialization of additive manufacturing (AM).
[src:boiler/astm-international] Headquartered in Washington, D.C., with a network of experts across the Americas, Europe, and Asia, the AM CoE focuses on bridging the gap between cutting-edge research and consensus-based standards.
[src:boiler/astm-international] These initiatives aim to close standardization gaps, support qualification frameworks, and promote the broader adoption of additive manufacturing technologies across the aerospace, defense industry, medical devices, automotive industry, and energy sectors.
[src:boiler/astm-international] In 2021, ASTM International acquired Wohlers Associates, a consulting firm and market intelligence provider in additive manufacturing and 3D printing.
[src:boiler/astm-international] Wohlers Associates provides industry analysis and forecasts covering hardware, software, materials, and applications related to additive manufacturing.
[src:boiler/astm-international] Funded by the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST), the Standardization Center of Excellence (SCOE) is a more recent initiative under ASTM International.
[src:boiler/astm-international] SCOE focuses on advancing innovation and standardization for critical and emerging technologies, offering a coordinated framework connecting R&D, standards development, workforce readiness, and regulatory alignment.
[src:boiler/astm-international] The SCOE enables cross-industry collaboration to ensure that next-generation technologies are developed, validated, and deployed with trusted, globally harmonized standards.
[src:boiler/astm-international] ASTM International has no role in requiring or enforcing compliance with its standards.
[src:boiler/astm-international] The standards may become mandatory when referenced by an external contract, corporation, regulation, law, or government.
[src:boiler/astm-international] In the United States, ASTM standards have been adopted by incorporation or reference in many federal, state, and municipal government regulations.
[src:boiler/astm-international] The 1995 National Technology Transfer and Advancement Act requires the Federal government to use privately developed consensus standards whenever possible.
[src:boiler/astm-international] The Act reflects what had long been recommended as best practice within the Federal government.
[src:boiler/astm-international] Other governments, including state and foreign, have also referenced ASTM standards.
[src:boiler/astm-international] Corporations doing international business may choose to reference an ASTM standard.
[src:boiler/astm-international] All toys sold in the United States must meet the safety requirements of ASTM F963, Standard Consumer Safety Specification for Toy Safety, as part of the Consumer Product Safety Improvement Act (CPSIA) of 2008.
[src:boiler/astm-international] The law makes the ASTM F963 standard a mandatory requirement for toys while the Consumer Product Safety Commission (CPSC) studies the standard's effectiveness and issues final consumer guidelines for toy safety.
[src:boiler/boiler] A **boiler** is a closed vessel in which fluid (generally water) is heated.
[src:boiler/boiler] The heated or vaporized fluid exits the boiler for use in various processes or heating applications, including water heating, central heating, boiler-based power generation, cooking, and sanitation.
[src:boiler/boiler] In a fossil fuel power plant using a steam cycle for power generation, the primary heat source will be combustion of coal, oil, or natural gas.
[src:boiler/boiler] In some cases byproduct fuel such as the carbon monoxide rich offgasses of a coke battery can be burned to heat a boiler; biofuels such as bagasse, where economically available, can also be used.
[src:boiler/boiler] In a nuclear power plant, boilers called steam generators are heated by the heat produced by nuclear fission.
[src:boiler/boiler] Where a large volume of hot gas is available from some process, a heat recovery steam generator or recovery boiler can use the heat to produce steam, with little or no extra fuel consumed; such a configuration is common in a combined cycle power plant where a gas turbine and a steam boiler are used.
[src:boiler/boiler] In all cases the combustion product waste gases are separate from the working fluid of the steam cycle, making these systems examples of external combustion engines.
[src:boiler/boiler] The pressure vessel of a boiler is usually made of steel (or alloy steel), or historically of wrought iron.
[src:boiler/boiler] Stainless steel, especially of the austenitic types, is not used in wetted parts of boilers due to corrosion and stress corrosion cracking.
[src:boiler/boiler] However, ferritic stainless steel is often used in superheater sections that will not be exposed to boiling water, and electrically heated stainless steel shell boilers are allowed under the European "Pressure Equipment Directive" for production of steam for sterilizers and disinfectors.
[src:boiler/boiler] In live steam models, copper or brass is often used because it is more easily fabricated in smaller size boilers.
[src:boiler/boiler] For much of the Victorian "age of steam", the only material used for boilermaking was the highest grade of wrought iron, with assembly by riveting.
[src:boiler/boiler] This iron was often obtained from specialist ironworks, such as those in the Cleator Moor (UK) area, noted for the high quality of their rolled plate, which was especially suitable for use in critical applications such as high-pressure boilers.
[src:boiler/boiler] In the 20th century, design practice moved towards the use of steel, with welded construction, which is stronger and cheaper, and can be fabricated more quickly and with less labour.
[src:boiler/boiler] Wrought iron boilers corrode far more slowly than their modern-day steel counterparts, and are less susceptible to localized pitting and stress-corrosion.
[src:boiler/boiler] That makes the longevity of older wrought-iron boilers far superior to that of welded steel boilers.
[src:boiler/boiler] Cast iron may be used for the heating vessel of domestic water heaters.
[src:boiler/boiler] Although such heaters are usually termed "boilers" in some countries, their purpose is usually to produce hot water, not steam, and so they run at low pressure and try to avoid boiling.
[src:boiler/boiler] The brittleness of cast iron makes it impractical for high-pressure steam boilers.
[src:boiler/boiler] The source of heat for a boiler is combustion of any of several fuels, such as wood, coal, oil, or natural gas.
[src:boiler/boiler] Electric steam boilers use resistance- or immersion-type heating elements.
[src:boiler/boiler] Nuclear fission is also used as a heat source for generating steam, either directly (BWR) or, in most cases, in specialised heat exchangers called "steam generators" (PWR).
[src:boiler/boiler] Heat recovery steam generators (HRSGs) use the heat rejected from other processes such as gas turbine.
[src:boiler/boiler] Direct method of boiler efficiency test is more usable or more common.
[src:boiler/boiler] A primitive "kettle" where a fire heats a partially filled water container from below.
[src:boiler/boiler] 18th-century Haycock boilers generally produced and stored large volumes of very low-pressure steam, often hardly above that of the atmosphere.
[src:boiler/boiler] These could burn wood or most often, coal.
[src:boiler/boiler] This is the type of boiler used in nearly all steam locomotives.
[src:boiler/boiler] Fire-tube boilers usually have a comparatively low rate of steam production, but high steam storage capacity.
[src:boiler/boiler] Fire-tube boilers mostly burn solid fuels, but are readily adaptable to those of the liquid or gas variety.
[src:boiler/boiler] Fire-tube boilers may also be referred to as "scotch-marine" or "marine" type boilers.
[src:boiler/boiler] In this type, tubes filled with water are arranged inside a furnace in a number of possible configurations.
[src:boiler/boiler] Often the water tubes connect large drums, the lower ones containing water and the upper ones steam and water; in other cases, such as a mono-tube boiler, water is circulated by a pump through a succession of coils.
[src:boiler/boiler] This type generally gives high steam production rates, but less storage capacity than fire-tube boilers.
[src:boiler/boiler] Water tube boilers can be designed to exploit any heat source and are generally preferred in high-pressure applications since the high-pressure water/steam is contained within small diameter pipes which can withstand the pressure with a thinner wall.
[src:boiler/boiler] These boilers are commonly constructed in place, roughly square in shape, and can be multiple stories tall.
[src:boiler/boiler] A flash boiler is a specialized type of water-tube boiler in which tubes are close together and water is pumped through them.
[src:boiler/boiler] A flash boiler differs from the type of mono-tube steam generator in which the tube is permanently filled with water.
[src:boiler/boiler] Flash boilers had some use in automobiles in the 19th century and this use continued into the early 20th century.
[src:boiler/boiler] The gases then pass through a conventional firetube boiler.
[src:boiler/boiler] but have met with little success in other countries.
[src:boiler/boiler] In a cast iron sectional boiler, sometimes called a "pork chop boiler" the water is contained inside cast iron sections.
[src:boiler/boiler] These sections are assembled on site to create the finished boiler.
[src:boiler/boiler] To define and secure boilers safely, some professional specialized organizations such as the American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME) develop standards and regulation codes.
[src:boiler/boiler] For instance, the ASME Boiler and Pressure Vessel Code is a standard providing a wide range of rules and directives to ensure compliance of the boilers and other pressure vessels with safety, security and design standards.
[src:boiler/boiler] Historically, boilers were a source of many serious injuries and property destruction due to poorly understood engineering principles.
[src:boiler/boiler] Thin and brittle metal shells can rupture, while poorly welded or riveted seams could open up, leading to a violent eruption of the pressurized steam.
[src:boiler/boiler] When water is converted to steam it expands to over 1,000 times its original volume and travels down steam pipes at over 100 kilometres per hour (62 mph).
[src:boiler/boiler] Because of this, steam is an efficient method of moving energy and heat around a site from a central boiler house to where it is needed, but without the right boiler feedwater treatment, a steam-raising plant will suffer from scale formation and corrosion.
[src:boiler/boiler] At best, this increases energy costs and can lead to poor quality steam, reduced efficiency, shorter plant life and unreliable operation.
[src:boiler/boiler] At worst, it can lead to catastrophic failure and loss of life.
[src:boiler/boiler] Collapsed or dislodged boiler tubes can also spray scalding-hot steam and smoke out of the air intake and firing chute, injuring the firemen who load the coal into the fire chamber.
[src:boiler/boiler] Extremely large boilers providing hundreds of horsepower to operate factories can potentially demolish entire buildings.
[src:boiler/boiler] A boiler that has a loss of feed water and is permitted to boil dry can be extremely dangerous.
[src:boiler/boiler] If feed water is then sent into the empty boiler, the small cascade of incoming water instantly boils on contact with the superheated metal shell and leads to a violent explosion that cannot be controlled even by safety steam valves.
[src:boiler/boiler] Draining of the boiler can also happen if a leak occurs in the steam supply lines that is larger than the make-up water supply could replace.
[src:boiler/boiler] The *Hartford Loop* was invented in 1919 by the Hartford Steam Boiler Inspection and Insurance Company as a method to help prevent this condition from occurring, and thereby reduce their insurance claims.
[src:boiler/boiler] When water is boiled the result is saturated steam, also referred to as "wet steam." Saturated steam, while mostly consisting of water vapor, carries some unevaporated water in the form of droplets.
[src:boiler/boiler] Saturated steam is useful for many purposes, such as cooking, heating and sanitation, but is not desirable when steam is expected to convey energy to machinery, such as a ship's propulsion system or the "motion" of a steam locomotive.
[src:boiler/boiler] This is because unavoidable temperature and/or pressure loss that occurs as steam travels from the boiler to the machinery will cause some condensation, resulting in liquid water being carried into the machinery.
[src:boiler/boiler] The water entrained in the steam may damage turbine blades or in the case of a reciprocating steam engine, may cause serious mechanical damage due to hydrostatic lock.
[src:boiler/boiler] Superheated steam boilers evaporate the water and then further heat the steam in a *superheater*, causing the discharged steam temperature to be substantially above the boiling temperature at the boiler's operating pressure.
[src:boiler/boiler] As the resulting "dry steam" is much hotter than needed to stay in the vaporous state it will not contain any significant unevaporated water.
[src:boiler/boiler] Also, higher steam pressure will be possible than with saturated steam, enabling the steam to carry more energy.
[src:boiler/boiler] Although superheating adds more energy to the steam in the form of heat there is no effect on pressure, which is determined by the rate at which steam is drawn from the boiler and the pressure settings of the safety valves.
[src:boiler/boiler] The fuel consumption required to generate superheated steam is greater than that required to generate an equivalent volume of saturated steam.
[src:boiler/boiler] However, the overall energy efficiency of the steam plant (the combination of boiler, superheater, piping and machinery) generally will be improved enough to more than offset the increased fuel consumption.
[src:boiler/boiler] Superheater operation is similar to that of the coils on an air conditioning unit, although for a different purpose.
[src:boiler/boiler] The steam piping is directed through the flue gas path in the boiler furnace, an area in which the temperature is typically between 1,300 and 1,600 degrees Celsius (2,372 and 2,912 degrees Fahrenheit).
[src:boiler/boiler] Some superheaters are radiant type, which as the name suggests, they absorb heat by radiation.
[src:boiler/boiler] Others are convection type, absorbing heat from a fluid.
[src:boiler/boiler] Some are a combination of the two types.
[src:boiler/boiler] Through either method, the extreme heat in the flue gas path will also heat the superheater steam piping and the steam within.
[src:boiler/boiler] The design of any superheated steam plant presents several engineering challenges due to the high working temperatures and pressures.
[src:boiler/boiler] One consideration is the introduction of feedwater to the boiler.
[src:boiler/boiler] The pump used to charge the boiler must be able to overcome the boiler's operating pressure, else water will not flow.
[src:boiler/boiler] As a superheated boiler is usually operated at high pressure, the corresponding feedwater pressure must be even higher, demanding a more robust pump design.
[src:boiler/boiler] High pressure, superheated steam can be extremely dangerous if it unintentionally escapes.
[src:boiler/boiler] To give the reader some perspective, the steam plants used in many U.S.
[src:boiler/boiler] Navy destroyers built during World War II operated at 600 psi (4,100 kPa; 41 bar) pressure and 850 degrees Fahrenheit (454 degrees Celsius) superheat.
[src:boiler/boiler] Also, small leaks that are not visible at the point of leakage could be lethal if an individual were to step into the escaping steam's path.
[src:boiler/boiler] Hence designers endeavor to give the steam-handling components of the system as much strength as possible to maintain integrity.
[src:boiler/boiler] Special methods of coupling steam pipes together are used to prevent leaks, with very high pressure systems employing welded joints to avoid leakage problems with threaded or gasketed connections.
[src:boiler/boiler] Supercritical steam generators are frequently used for the production of electric power.
[src:boiler/boiler] In contrast to a "subcritical boiler", a supercritical steam generator operates at such a high pressure (over 3,200 psi or 22 MPa) that the physical turbulence that characterizes boiling ceases to occur; the fluid is neither liquid nor gas but a supercritical fluid.
[src:boiler/boiler] There is no generation of steam bubbles within the water, because the pressure is above the critical pressure point at which steam bubbles can form.
[src:boiler/boiler] As the fluid expands through the turbine stages, its thermodynamic state drops below the critical point as it does work turning the turbine which turns the electrical generator from which power is ultimately extracted.
[src:boiler/boiler] The fluid at that point may be a mix of steam and liquid droplets as it passes into the condenser.
[src:boiler/boiler] This results in slightly less fuel use and therefore less greenhouse gas production.
[src:boiler/boiler] The term "boiler" should not be used for a supercritical pressure steam generator, as no "boiling" occurs in this device.
[src:boiler/boiler] A fuel-heated boiler must provide air to oxidize its fuel.
[src:boiler/boiler] Early boilers provided this stream of air, or *draught*, through the natural action of convection in a chimney connected to the exhaust of the combustion chamber.
[src:boiler/boiler] Since the heated flue gas is less dense than the ambient air surrounding the boiler, the flue gas rises in the chimney, pulling denser, fresh air into the combustion chamber.
[src:boiler/boiler] Most modern boilers depend on mechanical draught rather than natural draught.
[src:boiler/boiler] This is because natural draught is subject to outside air conditions and temperature of flue gases leaving the furnace, as well as the chimney height.
[src:boiler/boiler] All these factors make proper draught hard to attain and therefore make mechanical draught equipment much more reliable and economical.
[src:boiler/boiler] Types of draught can also be divided into *induced draught*, where exhaust gases are pulled out of the boiler; *forced draught*, where fresh air is pushed into the boiler; and *balanced draught*, where both effects are employed.
[src:boiler/boiler] Natural draught through the use of a chimney is a type of induced draught; mechanical draught can be induced, forced or balanced.
[src:boiler/boiler] There are two types of mechanical induced draught.
[src:boiler/boiler] The first is through use of a steam jet.
[src:boiler/boiler] The steam jet oriented in the direction of flue gas flow induces flue gases into the stack and allows for a greater flue gas velocity increasing the overall draught in the furnace.
[src:boiler/boiler] This method was common on steam driven locomotives which could not have tall chimneys.
[src:boiler/boiler] The second method is by simply using an induced draught fan (ID fan) which removes flue gases from the furnace and forces the exhaust gas up the stack.
[src:boiler/boiler] Almost all induced draught furnaces operate with a slightly negative pressure.
[src:boiler/boiler] Mechanical forced draught is provided by means of a fan forcing air into the combustion chamber.
[src:boiler/boiler] Air is often passed through an air heater; which, as the name suggests, heats the air going into the furnace to increase the overall efficiency of the boiler.
[src:boiler/boiler] Dampers are used to control the quantity of air admitted to the furnace.
[src:boiler/boiler] Forced draught furnaces usually have a positive pressure.
[src:boiler/boiler] Balanced draught is obtained through use of both induced and forced draught.
[src:boiler/boiler] This is more common with larger boilers where the flue gases have to travel a long distance through many boiler passes.
[src:boiler/boiler] The induced draught fan works in conjunction with the forced draught fan allowing the furnace pressure to be maintained slightly below atmospheric.
